The intercept of 2.7204 tells us that if a respondent has an education level of "0" (which is not really possible here, since the lowest level of education in our numeric variable is "1" being Elementary School), the regression predicts the person to rate their economic safety as being 2.7204 on a scale from 1-5.

The beta-coefficient of 0.0915 predicts that people of "1" higher education level (levels ranging from 1-6), will approximately rate their economic safety 0.0915 higher, if there is to be an association between the two variables.
